<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.pineglen.com/diamond.htm">Source.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
Even though the diamond is the hardest of all known gemstones, it is the simplest in composition. It is common carbon, like the graphite in a lead pencil, yet has a melting point of approximately 4,000 degrees centigrade, which is two and a half times greater than the melting point of steel.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 181<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/28/02 12:00:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=85>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Possible source for design answers.</span><hr size=1> So, yes diamond can melt. And since the numbers in this thread claim that the minimal temperature for a GCNR is 5000*C...... Thanks for helping answer my question on diamond. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 124<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/28/02 12:13:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=86>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Possible source for design answers.</span><hr size=1> Diamond is transparent to the wrong frequencies.  It is very tramsparent to infrared, but we need transparencies WAY higher in the spectrum.<br>
<br>
Also, I will repeat this again: The Lightbulb should never have to deal with any significant physical stresses.  The material strength of the Lightbulb is so tiny compared to the energies being unleashed in this thruster there is no way for anything physical to survive them.<br>
<br>
The only way to keep the Lightbulb intact is to engineer it so that it carries very little mechanical load (pressure balanced from the inside and the outside) and allows the radiative output of the core to flow through it with near perfect efficiency.<br>
<br>
Luckily, I think we can do both of those these days.<br>
<br>
Oh, and HAPPY THANKSGIVING!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     <br>
