<br>
Some more nitpicks:<br>
<br>
I didn't completely understand what exactly is happening inside the light bulb. As far as I understand it, there is a 3 phase flow: the UF4 fuel gas, a shielding gas and a coolant gas. The shielding gas flows between bulb surface and the fuel gas phase, forcing the fuel to remain in the center of the bulb? <br>
I see quite a lot problems in tying to keep this system stable and running in terms of fluid dynamics. Also, there is the problem of the coolant gas becoming contaminated with UF4, nuclear waste and spreading it everywhere in the &quot;heat sink&quot; chamber and blowing it eventually out through the nozzle. In order to keep the shielding gas moving, one will need turbo pumps. The problem here is how should this extremely hot gas be kept cold enough (for pumping) while not mixing it with a cooler gas? <br>
(Mixing is out of question because the shielding gas will be highly contaminated with nuclear reactants)<br>
<br>
From this follows that the bulb can only be cooled from the inside with a gas cycle that is seperated from the propellants, and remains constant in mass-&gt; basicly the shielding gas will be pushed through the microholes acting as a shield and coolant simultaneously. This is actually good, since it simplifies the system a little bit, but the larger problem still remains: how sould this gas be cooled? <br>
<br>
Incredibly high flow rates?-&gt;more mixing with fuel-&gt;more convective heat transfer with the fuel<br>
<br>
<br>
Any way this should keep us ocupied.. so lets go to my next little nitpick:<br>
<br>
The heat transfer to the propellant! It is anything but certain that with the planed propellant flow rates a sufficient heat transfer can occur with the planed temperatures. We will most likely have to force the propellants through a silicia labyrinth to ensure long enough exposure times...<br>
<br>
The next nitpick has more to do with engineering: It is going to extremely difficult to prevent the bulb from shattering. There are four sources from the tip of my head which will introduce stresses into this bulb: thermal stresses, a general pressure gradient between the layers of the bulbs, unsteadyness in the coolant/shielding gas flow and of course any accelerations will produce a force acting on the bulb. What one shouldn't forget, is that by drilling microholes into the bulb its yield strength will be reduced to a fraction of what it was before simply due to the new geometry.<br>
<br>
<br>
I have a few requests:<br>
Could someone please tell me from where I can get more info on the subject of nuclear propulsion? <br>
I am particularly interested in &quot;wire core reactors&quot; and &quot;foam reactors&quot; because I basicly don't know more about them than thier names.<br>
