<br>
First, I think you don't quite know what is going on in around the reactor. The coolant gas flows over the surface of the lightbulb, not in it, or at least that's what I understand it to do. Then there is the vortex buffer gas, the main containment of the reaction. Then there are two layers of UF6 before the core. The outermost is to absorb Gamma rays and neutrons. This layer does not undergo fission. The intermediate layer of UF6 is to absorb X-Rays and undergoes some fission. Then the core. <br>
