Questions: <br>
<br>
Hamster: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I'm so used to thinking in terms of reducing the mass to an absolute minimum that I hadn't thought about how nuclear propulsion would allow us to build sturdier vehicles in themselves.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yeah, it's a wonderful realization, isn't it?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   This sort of mental flash is the &quot;paradigm shift&quot; I was talking about way at the beginning of this thread.  Also, due to the nice gentle ride to orbit the Liberty Ship affords, that paradigm shift is even greater.  2 g's of acceleration is readily tolerated.  The physical requirements of the passenger and crew of the Liberty Ship can be quite a bit reduced from the already relaxed standards of the Space Shuttle.  <br>
<br>
Heck, if we are willing to accept a bit of added complexity in the flight regime, we can reduce the maximum G-loads on the flight up to orbit down to the 1.4 incurred at takeoff.  The SSME turbopumps are designed to be throttle-able, and the power generated by the gaseous cores can be readily fine-tuned by controlling the vorticity inside the lightbulb.  (I think.)<br>
<br>
This means the equipment designed for launch in the Liberty Ship can be much less sturdily built than gear meant to go up in the Shuttle, while paradoxically being HEAVIER.  This means less design work is needed, and less expensive materials are used.  <br>
<br>
Plus, volume counts!  The Liberty Ship could carry something like 38 geosynchronous satellites to orbit, along with 38 chemical fueled upper stages.  If a few of them malfunction, it is no longer a disaster, it is a maintenance issue.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Does anyone have any estimates on how much it would cost per ton to lift a payload to space using Mauk2's concept? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Dang, I never thought about it....  Well, lets toss a few numbers on the wall and see if they stick.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
&lt;Shrug&gt;   Lets use the Space Shuttle,  its the closest system we have.  I know you don't want to, but I don't have any idea how well an airline model could be applied to the Liberty Ship, and I will err on the side of caution.  If we can apply airliner standards to the Liberty Ship, then all bets on price are off.  (Think tickets to orbit for 100 dollars a seat.  Imagine how many people you can fit into a personnel module that masses a thousand tons. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
<br>
Ok, you have to pay for a launch ship, say it costs two hundred million.  Say the Liberty Ship costs 5 billion to build, mostly for research and dev work on the engines.  Lets say we replace all the lightbulbs after every flight, in the interest of paranoia, at a cost of 70 million.  Liquid hydrogen and enriched uranium is basically free on prices of this scale, so assume the 70 million for new lightbulbs also cover those costs.<br>
<br>
For launch facilities, we have to build a REALLY big Vehicle Assembly Building type structure, with MONSTER cranes.  (Handling the Liberty Ship cargo module is nothing to sneeze at, it's HEAVY.)  In addition, we have to be able to sail the launch ship into and out of the VAB.  Call it another 2 billion for ground facilities.<br>
<br>
Lets assume we have a vehicle lifespan of 100 flights.<br>
<br>
Now, ground maintenance....  The Space Shuttle costs a billion a launch, more or less, and almost all of that is spent on exhaustively and laboriously taking the thing to pieces and checking everything.  On the Liberty Ship, we just build the darn thing like a tank and don't worry about many of the simpler systems.  Plus, the Liberty Ship has a lower moving parts count and fewer systems.  An example: The Liberty Ship has no cargo bay door.  All the cargo rides on the top, and is released into orbit as a big chunk.  Simple is good.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
BUT, the Liberty Ship has those crazy powerful nuclear thrusters.....  It would be safe to say that at least at first, they will be handled with the most extreme care imaginable.<br>
<br>
So, lets say the Liberty Ship costs 600 million in maintenance per launch.  Add on 70 million for the lightbulbs, reaction mass, uranium hexaflouride, etc.<br>
<br>
670 million in per-flight maintenance and expendables costs.<br>
<br>
We also have 7.2 billion in fixed costs to repay, which is equal to 72 million per flight if we fly it 100 times.  Add in interest, say it costs say 130 million per flight to pay for the ground facilities.<br>
<br>
800 million per flight in total costs.  Add in 200 million a flight for profit.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   One billion dollars a flight, same as the Space Shuttle.  (Yes, I did it on purpose.)<br>
<br>
2 million pounds of cargo a flight, costing one billion dollars, is like what, 500 dollars a pound?  <br>
<br>
Not ultra cheap.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    Oh well, sorry!  <br>
<br>
If you're willing to make no profit, the cost drops to 400 per pound, though.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Plus, if you build, say, 5 of the Liberty Ships, things get much more interesting.  <br>
<br>
