<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Wait, is the hydrogen H2 or monoatomic hydrogen? If it's monoatomic, would that matter(ie would it react with O2)? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As I envision it, the Hydrogen is injected as cold dense gas, after having been used in liquid form to cool the lightbulb and reaction chamber/nozzle.  As it is heated, it breaks from H2 to monatomic form, and as it approaches 15,000 kelvin, it gets so hot that the electrons actually are stripped away from the protons, so you really have a plasma exiting the reaction chamber.  At those temperatures, no, it would not chemically react with the oxygen, the hydrogen ions are so energetic they can't be captured by the oxygen.<br>
<br>
Now, in the exhaust stream, as it cools, it would react, but at that point, its too late to extract that energy.  Luckily, it is so little energy compared to the gas core, it is of little worry.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
