I am no nuclear physicist or rocket scientist, I'm just too stubborn to give up.  Or to quote some famous smart guy, &quot;The only reason I can reach so high is because I stand on the shoulders of giants.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Plus, the Internet makes this stuff EASY.  Years ago I did a lot of tinkering with HLV's before I gave up, and getting data to work with now, after the web has come into being is SO much easier.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> because with these large temperature ranges, your fluids do not behave perfectly, and ideal gas law is most likely not applicable. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I know, and that frustrates me immensely, but I can't find anything better.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
However, I have read in a few places that the Ideal Gas Law worked quite well to describe the behavior of a plasma, since the main source of problems with the Ideal Gas Law arises from energy being dumped into spinning molecules, etc.  In a plasma, no molecues!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   (I could be wrong, but hey...)<br>
<br>
<br>
nebobgrenville:  You have expressed doubts I can keep the core critical without a moderator, and I am starting to worry you are right.  Now, modeling the fissile mass is gonna be NASTY, so I tried a little practice run first.<br>
<br>
Now, the practice run I decided to tackle was neutron absorption/scattering in the actual reaction chamber.  (This is easier, the hydrogen plasma is just simpler to deal with.)  <br>
<br>
Okay, according to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://qgp.physics.iastate.edu/phys524/Lectures/lect9.PDF"> this .pdf </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> the scattering cross-section of gaseous hydrogen is 130 barn.  BUT, according to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.tpub.com/doenuclearphys/nuclearphysics41.htm"> this page, </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> the hotter an atom is, the smaller it's cross-section becomes, due to the nucleus slamming and banging around.  At 15,500 kelvin, the scattering cross-section of hydrogen shrinks to a miserable 19 barn or so.  Blah.<br>
<br>
Now, according to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.tpub.com/fluid/ch3e.htm"> this page, </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> as you compress a gas, it gets denser, and as you heat it, it gets less dense.  Plugging in 3000 psi pressure and 15,500 kelvin temperatures, I arrive at a density for the plasma inside the chamber that is quadruple (roughly) that of gaseous hydrogen at normal conditions.<br>
<br>
Now, according to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.tpub.com/doenuclearphys/nuclearphysics40.htm"> this page </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> the Neutron Mean Free Path can be calculated from the molar density and the cross-section of the material.  Plugging in the information I calculated above, and assuming my crummy math skillz did not blow up on the way, I arrive at a Neutron Mean Free Path inside the reaction chamber of 275 cm.<br>
<br>
What this means, is on average, a fast neutron will interact with this plasma once every 2.75 meters.  By default, this is now the minimum distance I am willing to allow between the fissile core and the outside of the thruster.  Luckily, the chamber I am envisioning is quite phat enough to allow this.  <br>
<br>
So, every time a neutron interacts with a hydrogen nucleus, it loses on average 63 percent of its energy.  Most of the neutrons produced by the fission of U235 have an average energy of 2 Mev, and about 1 percent of the energy of the fission reaction is captured by that neutron.  So, in an 80 gigawatt thruster, 800 megawatts are thrown out as neutrons. <br>
<br>
If the reaction in the core is to be self sustaining, a smidgeon more than half of those have to cause more fissions.  The other half escape the core, or 400 megawatts worth.<br>
<br>
Of the 400 megawatts, 63 percent or maybe a bit more is absorbed by the reaction mass plasma in the reaction chamber and goes out the nozzle.    This leaves 148 megawatts of neutrons to escape the thruster.  Hmmmm.<br>
<br>
Well, I'll work out tossing a beryllium layer around the reaction chamber.  Luckily, beryllium is light and strong, so it'll be useful as a structural element.  &lt;sigh&gt;  <br>
<br>
Now, these neutrons pose a real problem to the crew!  Since my thruster may be leakier than I expected, I worked up some rough numbers for the scattering efficiency of the liguid hydrogen in the fuel tank.  It turns out I have no worries there.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The scattering cross section of liquid hydrogen is TINY, only 4 barns.  Luckily, liquid hydrogen has WAY more atoms per centimeter than gaseous hydrogen, and I have 50 METERS of liquid hydrogen in that tank to work with.  After doing the math (assuming I got it right) the Mean Free Path in LH2 is 58 centimeters.  To completely thermalize a neutron in hydrogen (IE, slow it down to where it's going the same speed as everything else) takes about 16 collisions, with the neutron losing two/thirds of its energy with each collision.<br>
<br>
So, very, very few neutrons make it past the huge fuel tank to threaten the crew.  Most of them slow to a crawl after at most 8 meters of liquid hydrogen.  <br>
<br>
(NOTE: In the descent phase, the tank is nearly empty of liquid hydrogen.  Luckily, the MFP in cool gas is still only 1.5 meters, so nearly all neutrons are still fully thermalized only 24 meters into the 55 meter tall tank.  It makes  HELLUVA good rad shield!)<br>
<br>
Now, this brings us to another problem:  If hydrogen captures a thermal neutron, a REALLY mean gamma ray gets emitted.  Now, according to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://dspace.dial.pipex.com/johncaunt/neutron_shielding_review.htm"> this site, </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> normal neutron shielding materials use plastics with lots of hydrogen in them to slow the neutrons down, then uses boron to mop them up safely.  Boron has  HUGE absorption cross-section, and does not emit those nasty gamma rays, either.  <br>
<br>
So, our main hydrogen tank serves as a VERY good neutron shield, even against the gigantic neutron emissions of the Liberty Ship thrusters, as long as we make sure there are lots of heavily borated slosh baffles and perforated sheets of boron in the tank to mop up the slowed neutrons.  Since I am a firm believer in redundancy, the crew couches used on the ride up and down will have a 5 centimeter thick slab of <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://dspace.dial.pipex.com/johncaunt/neutron_atten_factors.htm"> borated polyethylene </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> under them.  If that webpage is to be believed, 2 inches of that stuff should do quite well as a &quot;failsafe&quot; backstop.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Now, quite a lot of energy gets dumped into the tank, but luckily that tank is drained of the warmest hydrogen first, so it is not an issue.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Plus, the neutron flux out of the thruster is not spherically symmetrical, the most actively fissioning parts of the core are pushed as far down the lightbulb as is feasible, to put the thickest possible blanket of uranium between there and the structure of the ship.<br>
<br>
Whew!  Now to figure out exact numbers for beryllium neutron reflection....  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Ok, got a little side-tracked there, more answers:<br>
<br>
dio82:<br>
