<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Ok, seriously.  <br>
<br>
(As a note, these were GREAT questions, thank you!)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> As far as I understand it, there is a 3 phase flow: the UF4 fuel gas, a shielding gas and a coolant gas. The shielding gas flows between bulb surface and the fuel gas phase, forcing the fuel to remain in the center of the bulb? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hrrrrm.  Well, I have not decided if there is a seperate coolant gas inside the lightbulb.  The entire inside of the lightbulb has to get pretty close to a thermal equilibrium at 25,000 K, so that the radiative cooling mechanism will work.  There is a MINIMUM gradiant of 10,000K across the bulb, and most of the heavy cooling is done via that mechanism.<br>
<br>
That said, we have to do something to keep the innermost layer of the silica bulb intact.  I have been thinking of a sub-loop which siphons off a small portion of the buffer gas at the top of the bulb, expands it to pre-cool it, then runs it through a heat exchanger with the cool hydrogen gas leaving the lightbulb on its way into the main injection loop.  A portion of this cooled buffer gas is then run through a small turbopump and the high energy output of that pump is used to power a venturi pump to keep the high temp vortex under control.  Most of the cooled buffer gas goes into the innermost open space of the lightbulb and is bled out on the inside of the bulb.  <br>
<br>
In this way, the inside of the bulb is kept as a totally seperate system from the reaction chamber, but some provision is made for a gas layer on the inside of the lightbulb to resist abrasion and corrosion.  <br>
<br>
To recap:<br>
The outer layers of the lightbulb are cooled with hydrogen and bleed outwards, the inner layers are cooled with buffer gas, a portion of which is cooled in a non-mixing heat exchanger with the hydrogen and is bled inwards.  <br>
<br>
This also makes the inside of the lightbulb a constant-volume system, which is mucho nice.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I see quite a lot problems in tying to keep this system stable and running in terms of fluid dynamics. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Luckily for us, we have BIG computers these days.  But I do have to agree with you.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> how sould this gas be cooled? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I suspect that heat exchanger will be an impressive piece of hardware.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
One simple way to drop the temps enough to allow the gas to be handled is to expand it's volume, a LOT, dropping the temps.  Pump it at low pressure, then dump the energy you imparted back into the denser, hotter stuff using the venturi pump I mentioned before.  <br>
<br>
This'll take a BIG computer.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   But I don't think it's anywhere near a show stopper.  <br>
