Yeah, I concur.  If you will notice, I placed an &quot;eddy structure&quot; in my crappy diagram of the thruster on my ghetto webpage.  That structure is there to increase the dwell time of the reaction mass in the chamber.  I am loathe to put too much structure inside that chamber, the conditions in there are HARSH.  The exact answer to this will have to be part of the engine dev work that obviously needs to happen.  <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> It is going to extremely difficult to prevent the bulb from shattering.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Heh.  That's putting it mildly.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I said, WAAAAY back at the beginning of the thread, that I felt keeping the bulb intact was going to be a BEAR.  Most folks have been picking on the tranmissivity problem, but I feel I have finally put that one to death.<br>
<br>
So, we are back to keeping the bulb intact.<br>
<br>
We are going to have to have some SERIOUS feedback controls on the hydrogen and buffer gas coolant pumps.  I envision some sort of a flexible polymer membrane between the two systems, so the two loops are in pressure equilibrium.  Furthermore, follow my thinking here: We have a three layer lightbulb, which means there are two open spaces in it, one inner and one outer.  <br>
<br>
The outer space is full of cold hydrogen.  The inner space is full of cooled buffer gas.  The outermost layer of silica is full of micropores, and bleeds hydrogen outwards.  The innermost layer of silica is full of micropores, and bleeds buffer gas inwards.<br>
<br>
Now, the two gases should be in pressure equilibrium.  If that is the case, we can then riddle the middle layer of silica with micropores also.  If there are no localized pressure variations around the silica bulb, no exchange ever happens.  If something bad happens, we can bleed gas (in SMALL amounts) between the layers.  This would trigger a vacuum scram, btw.  <br>
<br>
I would rather bleed a small amount of buffer gas than bust that bulb, ANY day.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
As for acceleration stresses, at the mild G's the Liberty Ship operates at, I cannot see them being a problem.  If the bulb is sturdy enough to survive the reaction chamber, the g stress will not phase it a bit.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> What one shouldn't forget, is that by drilling microholes into the bulb its yield strength will be reduced to a fraction of what it was before simply due to the new geometry. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hrrrrm.  Do you have any links to the magnitude of this reduction?  I have often said, for this bulb to survive, it must not be forced to withstand physical stresse, meaning it must be pressure balanced.    That said, it has to have SOME degree of strength.....  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
